div.div:
EC2 (launch_type = 'EC2') jobs have the following pros:
Cached images, leading to low latency between Prefect scheduler and job start.
Always have at least 1+ EC2 instances up - job run is more-or-less guaranteed...
... unless the EC2 gets hit with tons of jobs all at once, eating up all reservation space and not having enough time to trigger auto-scaling.
We should keep mission-critical, high frequency, non-intensive jobs here. Anything running more than every 6 hours is 'high frequency'.

switch.text: EC2 (launch_type = 'EC2') jobs have the following pros:...

div.div:
Fargate (launch_type='FARGATE') is the serverless offering for running containers.
Requires an ECR pull
on every job run
. Causes some latency for job start.
More expensive than EC2, assuming we maximized utilization on EC2.
Will never run into CPU/Memory over-usage,
as long as we set appropriate values in our deployment.
Cost incurred is subject to a 1-minute minimum. Jobs running faster than this cause excess cost.
It is possible (although rare) for Fargate not to be available temporarily.
We should keep longer running, lower frequency, resource intensive jobs here.

div.div:
Fargate Spot (launch_type='FARGATE_SPOT') is a variation on Fargate. Everything about Fargate still holds, plus:
Spot deployments can be killed with a 2-minute warning signaled to the container.
Price is based entirely on demand. In general, cost is roughly 1/4th of normal Fargate.
Anything that we plan to run in Fargate but can be designed to handle the 2-minute warning should be run here. We can make use of Prefect 'retries' to handle crashes due to infrastructure deaths.

div.div:
ECS deployments require you to keep the following in mind:
Every job will run as a clean-slate - if something is not git tracked, it won't be available. All 'writes' (and most reads too) should be made to a remote store.
Each job will have resource constraints. It is on the developer to assess appropriate values here. As a rule of thumb, start low and increase as needed during testing.
If possible, design your workflow for Fargate Spot (see bottom)
